#                                                              -*-org-*-
#+TITLE: The Dezyne server, services, client.
#+OPTIONS: toc:2          only include two levels in TOC

Dezyne is built and deployed using [[https://gnu.org/s/guix][Guix]] 53f21642729e4786141c072dd835b04cb85dfe28.  See `Setup Guix' below.

* Update Guix

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  guix pull --commit 53f21642729e4786141c072dd835b04cb85dfe28
  #+END_SRC

* Get it

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  mkdir -p src
  cd src && git clone git.oban.verum.com:~buildmaster/development.git
  #+END_SRC

* Build it
** Create a build environment

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  guix environment -l guix.scm
  #+END_SRC

or, for a richer environment
  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  guix environment -m release/manifest.scm
  #+END_SRC

** Configure and make
  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  ./configure
  make
  #+END_SRC

** Run uninstalled programs

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  ./pre-inst-env gdzn ...
  ./pre-inst-env dzn ...
  #+END_SRC

** Run regression test

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  ./pre-inst-env guix environment dezyne-services dezyne-regression-test
  ./pre-inst-env test test/hello/helloworld

  ./pre-inst-env test test/regression
  #+END_SRC

*** Run regression through node dzn client, daemon and server

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  guix environment -l guix.scm
  DZN=dzn ./pre-inst-env test test/hello/helloworld
  #+END_SRC

* Create or update a persistent build environment
** in your default profile

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  guix package -m release/manifest.scm
  #+END_SRC

** or in a special named profile

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  guix package -p ~/.config/guix/verum -m release/manifest.scm
  #+END_SRC

use it

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  GUIX_PROFILE=~/.config/guix/verum/etc/profile . ~/.config/guix/verum/etc/profile
  #+END_SRC

* Build Guix packages

** From local work tree, uncommited

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  guix build -f guix.scm
  #+END_SRC

** Build from public git

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  git_oban=http://git.oban.verum.com/voornaamachternaa ./pre-inst-env guix build dezyne-pack
  #+END_SRC

** Build from local git
*** Setup git daemon

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  mkdir -p $HOME/git-daemon
  ln -s $HOME/src/development $HOME/git-daemon/development.git
  #+END_SRC

*** Start git daemon

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  git daemon --base-path=$HOME/git-daemon --export-all &
  #+END_SRC

* Build vm

  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  ./pre-inst-env guix system vm guix/dezyne/system/os.scm
  #+END_SRC

** Run vm
  #+BEGIN_SRC bash
  /gnu/store/...-run-vm.sh  -m 2G -net nic -net user,hostfwd=tcp::10022-:22,hostfwd=tcp::13000-:3000
  #+END_SRC

** Build and run vm
  $(./pre-inst-env guix system vm guix/dezyne/system/os.scm) -m 2G -net nic -net user,hostfwd=tcp::10022-:22,hostfwd=tcp::13000-:3000

* Editing Scheme files

You should not code dialect of Lisp without Paredit.  Add to you
~/.emacs init file

  #+BEGIN_SRC elisp
  (when (require 'paredit nil t)
    (add-hook 'scheme-mode-hook #'enable-paredit-mode)
    (add-hook 'emacs-lisp-mode-hook #'enable-paredit-mode))
  #+END_SRC

Geiser gives you jump to definition (M-.) and jump-to-documentation
(C-d-d).

  #+BEGIN_SRC elisp
  (when (require 'geiser nil t) (add-hook 'scheme-mode-hook #'geiser-mode))
  #+END_SRC

* Setup Guix

** On Ubuntu

   As root (sudo -i) do
   #+BEGIN_SRC bash
   wget -O setup-guix.sh 'http://git.oban.verum.com/?p=buildmaster/development.git;a=blob_plain;f=release/setup-guix.sh;hb=refs/heads/master'
   chmod +x setup-guix.sh
   ./setup-guix.sh
   #+END_SRC

   As user do
   #+BEGIN_SRC bash
   wget -O setup-guix-user.sh 'http://git.oban.verum.com/?p=buildmaster/development.git;a=blob_plain;f=release/setup-guix-user.sh;hb=refs/heads/master'
   chmod +x setup-guix-user.sh
   ./setup-guix-user.sh
   #+END_SRC

** Or install [[https://guix.gnu.org][Guix System]]
